  "grammar": [
    {
      "id": "g-vocative",
      "title": "The Vocative Case: Forms of Address",
      "explanation": "The <strong>vocative case</strong> is used for direct address \u2014 calling out to someone. In Greek, vocative forms are often preceded by the particle <strong>\u1f66</strong> (O). For 1st declension feminines, the vocative singular is the same as the nominative. For 2nd declension masculines, the vocative singular typically ends in <strong>-\u03b5</strong>. In the opening of Antigone, the whole phrase '\u1f62 \u03ba\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u1f78\u03bd \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u03ac\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03bf\u03bd \u1f38\u03c3\u03bc\u03ae\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03ac\u03c1\u03b1' is one extended vocative \u2014 Antigone addressing her sister.",
      "examples": [
        { "greek": "\u1f66 \u1f04\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u1f08\u03b8\u03b7\u03bd\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03b9", "english": "O men of Athens (vocative plural)" },
        { "greek": "\u1f62 \u1f38\u03c3\u03bc\u03ae\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03ac\u03c1\u03b1", "english": "O dear Ismene (vocative with \u03ba\u03ac\u03c1\u03b1)" }
      ],
      "tip": "When you see \u1f66 or \u1f62 at the start of a phrase, someone is being addressed directly. The vocative is the case of calling, pleading, and commanding."
    },
    {
      "id": "g-compounds",
      "title": "Compound Words in Greek",
      "explanation": "Greek loves building compound words by joining two roots. <strong>\u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u03ac\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2</strong> combines \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u03cc\u03c2 (self/same) + \u1f00\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03cc\u03c2 (sibling, literally 'from the same womb': a- + delphys). This is enormously productive in Greek: \u03c6\u03b9\u03bb\u03cc\u03c3\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 (philo + sophos = lover of wisdom), \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1 (demos + kratos = people + power). Understanding compound formation helps you guess meanings of unfamiliar words.",
      "examples": [
        { "greek": "\u03b1\u1f50\u03c4-\u03ac\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 = self + sibling", "english": "own sibling (of the same parents)" },
        { "greek": "\u03c6\u03b9\u03bb\u03cc-\u03c3\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 = loving + wisdom", "english": "philosopher (lover of wisdom)" }
      ],
      "tip": "When you see a long Greek word, try splitting it at natural breaks. The first element often modifies or qualifies the second."
    }
  ],

